data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>`, which checks the type and returns the cast result:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The generic overload (MSTest v3.3+) returns the casted object, so you can keep asserting on it. If the type doesn't match, the test fails with a clear message instead of throwing an `InvalidCastException`.

For older MSTest versions without the generic return, use:

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
```
